How to decode a 2009 MINI Hardtop VIN
Characters 1-3 of a 2009 MINI Hardtop VIN
World Manufacturer Identifiers (WMIs) are a crucial aspect of a vehicle’s unique identification, serving as the first three characters in the 17-character Vehicle Identification Number (VIN). Each WMI is dedicated to a specific manufacturer and often provides additional information such as the country of manufacture and vehicle type. For instance, vehicles produced by BMW AG in Munich, Germany, for the years 2009 through 2024, including passenger cars like the 2009 Mini Hardtop, embody a WMI that precisely identifies BMW AG as the manufacturer. This system ensures that every car can be individually traced back to its maker, model year, and type, offering valuable data for registration, service, and recall purposes. Such identifiers not only streamline automotive logistics but also enhance global safety and compliance standards.

Check the door post on the driver-side where the front door latches, which is another common place where the VIN might be found on your 2009 Mini Hardtop.
Examine under the hood; there is usually a VIN plate located on the firewall of the Mini Hardtop 2009.

For the 2009 Dodge Grand Caravan, two different WMIs are used, reflecting their manufacturing locations and parent companies. The WMI “2D8” is assigned to Dodge Grand Caravans produced by FCA Canada Inc. in Windsor, Ontario, Canada, while “1D8” represents those manufactured by FCA US LLC in Auburn Hills, Michigan, United States. Both WMIs categorize the Dodge Grand Caravan as a Multipurpose Passenger Vehicle (MPV), highlighting the international footprint of its production. World Manufacturer Identifier (WMI) codes are a unique sequence of three letters or numbers assigned to every vehicle manufacturer around the globe. These codes form the initial part of the Vehicle Identification Number (VIN), which helps in identifying key aspects of the vehicle, such as its manufacturer, model year, and the location where it was made. For example, the WMI “JTD” is designated to Toyota Motor Corporation, indicating that the vehicle is manufactured by Toyota. Specifically, if a Toyota Prius from the 2014 model year has a VIN starting with “JTD,” it identifies the vehicle as being made by Toyota in Toyota City, Aichi Prefecture, Japan, and categorizes it as a passenger car.
